To terminate a C program, you can use the exit() function. This function takes an integer as an argument, which is the status code that is returned to the operating system. The default status code is 0, which means the program terminated normally. If you want to indicate an error, you can pass a non-zero status code.

Here is an example of how to use the exit() function:

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // Your code here
    exit(0); // Terminate the program with status code 0
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the program will terminate with a status code of 0, indicating that it terminated normally. If you want to indicate an error, you can pass a non-zero status code:

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // Your code here
    exit(1); // Terminate the program with status code 1
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the program will terminate with a status code of 1, indicating that it terminated with an error.
